INSERT INTO public.help_entries VALUES ('98330dfa-ae8a-4a7f-a6fa-18a5bf36aebc', 'User Management', 'Guide: Create/edit users/roles, assign permissions (user:manage, role:manage). Use admin UI for configs.

User operations:
1. Create users: Navigate to Users Management. Enter username, email, name, and assign role. Set password or enable password reset.
', 'User Management', 'Guide: Create/edit users/roles, assign permissions (user:manage, role:manage). Use admin UI for configs.

User operations:
1. Create users: Navigate to Users Management. Enter username, email, name, and assign role. Set password or enable password reset.
2. Edit users: Update user details, change roles, modify permissions. Users can be activated or deactivated.
3. Assign roles: Select appropriate role for each user. Roles determine default permissions and access levels.
4. Client assignment: For Client role users, assign to specific client for data isolation.

Role management:
- Create custom roles: Define new roles with specific permission sets
- Edit roles: Modify role permissions and descriptions
- Permission assignment: Assign permissions to roles using role:manage permission
- View role permissions: Review which permissions are assigned to each role

Permissions:
- user:manage: Required for user CRUD operations
- role:manage: Required for role and permission management
- config:edit: Required for system configuration changes

Best practices:
- Use strong passwords and enable password policies
- Assign minimal required permissions (principle of least privilege)
- Regularly review user access and deactivate unused accounts
- Document role changes and permission modifications', 'administrator', true, '2026-01-10 19:32:31.030314', NULL, '2026-01-10 19:32:31.030314', NULL);
INSERT INTO public.help_entries VALUES ('33400c23-e3e6-42ef-8c0b-e7621409ba65', 'EAV Configuration', 'Configure custom attributes using Entity-Attribute-Value (EAV) model:

EAV overview:
The EAV model enables administrators to define custom attributes for various entity types without schema changes, providing flexibility for laboratory-specific requiremen', 'EAV Configuration', 'Configure custom attributes using Entity-Attribute-Value (EAV) model:

EAV overview:
The EAV model enables administrators to define custom attributes for various entity types without schema changes, providing flexibility for laboratory-specific requirements.

Custom attributes configuration:
1. Access EAV config: Navigate to Custom Attributes Management in admin UI.
2. Create attribute: Define attribute name, entity type (sample, test, etc.), data type (text, number, date, boolean), and validation rules.
3. Set visibility: Configure which roles can view and edit custom attributes.
4. Define defaults: Set default values and required flags as needed.

Entity types supported:
- Samples: Custom fields for sample metadata
- Tests: Additional test configuration attributes
- Results: Extended result data fields
- Projects: Project-specific custom attributes

EAV editing:
- Edit existing attributes: Modify data types, validation, and visibility
- Deactivate attributes: Disable without deleting to preserve historical data
- View attribute usage: See where custom attributes are used across entities
- Export/import: Backup and restore custom attribute configurations

Data management:
- Custom attribute values are stored in EAV tables
- Values are queryable and filterable in admin UI
- Historical values are preserved for audit purposes
- Bulk updates supported for custom attribute values

Requires permission: config:edit', 'administrator', true, '2026-01-10 19:32:31.030314', NULL, '2026-01-10 19:32:31.030314', NULL);
INSERT INTO public.help_entries VALUES ('bd27847c-2bcc-4d15-a645-6ccda5a43657', 'Row Level Security (RLS)', 'Manage Row Level Security policies for data isolation:

RLS overview:
Row Level Security (RLS) ensures users can only access data they are authorized to view. Policies are enforced at the database level for comprehensive security.

RLS policy management:
', 'Row Level Security (RLS)', 'Manage Row Level Security policies for data isolation:

RLS overview:
Row Level Security (RLS) ensures users can only access data they are authorized to view. Policies are enforced at the database level for comprehensive security.

RLS policy management:
1. Review policies: Check existing RLS policies on tables (samples, results, projects, etc.). Policies are defined in database migrations.
2. Policy structure: Policies use USING clauses to filter rows based on user role, project access, and client assignments.
3. Admin bypass: Administrator role bypasses RLS restrictions to access all data for system administration.
4. Client isolation: Client users see only data associated with their assigned client_id.

Data isolation:
- Project-based: Users see samples/projects they are assigned to
- Client-based: Client users see only their client''s data
- Role-based: Different roles have different access levels
- Cross-project access: Lab Managers can access multiple projects

Policy configuration:
- Policies are created via Alembic migrations
- Use current_user_id() function to identify current user
- Use is_admin() function to check administrator status
- Policies apply to SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE operations

Testing RLS:
- Verify policies work correctly for each role
- Test data isolation between clients
- Ensure administrators can access all data
- Validate project-based access restrictions

Requires permission: config:edit (for policy modifications)', 'administrator', true, '2026-01-10 19:32:31.030314', NULL, '2026-01-10 19:32:31.030314', NULL);
INSERT INTO public.help_entries VALUES ('383d661c-2cb5-4747-b359-d5cf09296997', 'System Configuration', 'Manage system-wide configurations and settings:

Configuration areas:
1. Container types: Define container types available for sample storage. Configure dimensions, capacity, and position support (for plates).
2. Analyses: Create and configure analyses wi', 'System Configuration', 'Manage system-wide configurations and settings:

Configuration areas:
1. Container types: Define container types available for sample storage. Configure dimensions, capacity, and position support (for plates).
2. Analyses: Create and configure analyses with associated analytes. Set units, significant figures, and validation rules.
3. Test batteries: Define test batteries with ordered analyses. Configure optional flags and sequences.
4. Lists: Manage list values for status fields, sample types, matrices, and other enumerated fields.
5. Units: Configure measurement units and conversion factors.

Container type management:
- Create container types: Define new container types with specifications
- Edit types: Modify container properties and requirements
- Position support: Enable row/column positions for plate-based containers
- Capacity settings: Configure maximum samples per container

Analysis configuration:
- Create analyses: Define new analyses with name and description
- Configure analytes: Add analytes to analyses with units and validation
- Set defaults: Configure default values and required flags
- Validation rules: Define numeric ranges and format requirements

Test battery setup:
- Create batteries: Define test batteries with multiple analyses
- Set sequence: Order analyses within battery
- Optional flags: Mark analyses as optional in battery
- Usage tracking: Monitor which batteries are used most frequently

List management:
- Create lists: Define new list types (status, sample_type, etc.)
- Add values: Populate lists with allowed values
- Edit values: Modify existing list entries
- Deactivate: Remove values without deleting (preserve historical data)

Requires permission: config:edit', 'administrator', true, '2026-01-10 19:32:31.030314', NULL, '2026-01-10 19:32:31.030314', NULL);
INSERT INTO public.help_entries VALUES ('ce2abd2b-bd5d-4bcf-9892-2cfa62372702', 'Data Management', 'Oversee data operations and system maintenance:

Data oversight:
1. View all data: As administrator, access all samples, tests, results, and projects regardless of RLS restrictions.
2. Audit trails: Review created_at, modified_at, created_by, and modified', 'Data Management', 'Oversee data operations and system maintenance:

Data oversight:
1. View all data: As administrator, access all samples, tests, results, and projects regardless of RLS restrictions.
2. Audit trails: Review created_at, modified_at, created_by, and modified_by fields for all entities.
3. Data integrity: Monitor referential integrity and foreign key relationships.
4. Bulk operations: Perform bulk updates and data migrations as needed.

Project management:
- Create projects: Set up new projects with client associations
- Assign users: Add users to projects with appropriate access
- Monitor progress: Track sample accessioning and testing progress
- Update status: Modify project status and metadata

Batch oversight:
